Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #saucepan on medium-high heat, add the onion and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir together and cook until really soft, ~{7-8%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

While the onion cooks, trim the @green beans{150%g} and chop into thirds. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped, stalks and all).

Once the onion is nicely softened, add the @balsamic vinegar{1%tbsp} and cook for ~{1%minute} more, then add the @bulgur wheat{180%g} along with the @water{300%ml}. Stir in the @vegetable stock powder{1%tsp} and bring to the boil. Simmer for ~{1%minute}, then cover the mixture with a #lid, remove from the heat and leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes}, or until the rest of the meal is ready.

Ten minutes before the bulgur wheat is cooked, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the beans and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir-fry until they are softened and are slightly charred, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once the beans are tender, add the @king prawns{150%g} to the pan along with the garlic. Stir-fry until the prawns are cooked, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the way through.

Once cooked, remove from the heat and add the @soy sauce{25%ml} and @honey{15%ml}. Stir together.

Fluff up the bulgur wheat with a #fork, add the prawns, beans, any sauce left in the pan and half the parsley. Stir together. Add salt and pepper to taste, then serve in #bowls{} with the remaining parsley sprinkled on top. Enjoy!